Certainly! Below is a simple HTML file that creates a web app with two big circles using embedded CSS and JavaScript. You can copy and paste this code into a `.html` file and open it in a web browser to see the result.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Two Big Circles</title>
    <style>
        body {
            display: flex;
            justify-content: center;
            align-items: center;
            height: 100vh;
            margin: 0;
            background-color: #f0f0f0;
        }
        .circle {
            width: 200px;
            height: 200px;
            border-radius: 50%;
            position: relative;
            margin: 20px;
        }
        .circle1 {
            background-color: #3498db; /* Blue */
        }
        .circle2 {
            background-color: #e74c3c; /* Red */
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="circle circle1"></div>
    <div class="circle circle2"></div>

    <script>
        // Optional: Add interactivity
        const circles = document.querySelectorAll('.circle');
        circles.forEach(circle => {
            circle.addEventListener('click', () => {
                alert(`You clicked on the ${circle.classList.contains('circle1') ? 'blue' : 'red'} circle!`);
            });
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation:
- **HTML Structure**: The body contains two `div` elements representing the circles.
- **CSS Styles**: The circles are styled to be circular with a specific size and color. The body is centered using Flexbox.
- **JavaScript**: An event listener is added to each circle to show an alert when clicked, indicating which circle was clicked.

You can modify the colors, sizes, and other properties as needed!
